Basic Mental Model

GitHub stores your source code. When you run it, you are starting a process 
on your machine.

Docker Hub stores Docker images. When you run an image, you are starting a 
container, which is an isolated running instance of that image.

Core Docker Commands
docker ps               # list all running containers
docker images           # list all available images
docker kill <id>        # stop a running container
docker rmi <image_id>   # remove an image
Docker Compose

Docker Compose is a tool used to define and run multi-container applications
using a single YAML file. Instead of manually running multiple docker run 
commands, you define services (e.g., backend, database), networks, and 
volumes in one file.

All containers started through Docker Compose are automatically connected 
through a shared network, allowing them to communicate easily.

It is primarily used for local development and testing rather than 
production deployment, where more advanced orchestration tools 
(like Kubernetes) are preferred.

You typically start everything with:

docker-compose up
Running an Express + Prisma Project
Manual Installation (Without Docker)

This requires setting up everything directly on your system:

Update .env with database credentials
Run database migrations
Generate ORM client
Build and start the app
npx prisma migrate      # apply database schema changes
npx prisma generate     # generate Prisma client
npm run build           # compile project
npm run start           # start server
Docker-Based Installation

This approach removes the need to install dependencies locally and ensures 
consistency.

docker network create user_project  
# create an isolated network so containers can talk to each other

docker run --network user_project --name postgres \
-e POSTGRES_PASSWORD=your_password \
-d -p 5432:5432 postgres  
# start PostgreSQL container
# attaches it to the network
# sets password via environment variable
# runs in detached mode (-d)
# maps container port 5432 to host port 5432

docker build -t user_app .  
# build Docker image from Dockerfile in current directory

docker run --network user_project -p 3000:3000 user_app  
# start your backend container
# attaches to same network so it can access postgres
# exposes app on port 3000
Docker Compose Installation

With Docker Compose, the above setup is simplified into a single 
configuration file.

Steps:

Install Docker and Docker Compose
Define services (backend + database) in docker-compose.yml
Run everything together:
docker-compose up
# builds images (if needed) and starts all services together
CI/CD Pipeline with Docker

Docker integrates cleanly into CI/CD pipelines, enabling consistent builds 
and deployments.

Using GitHub Actions as an example:

CI (Build and Validate)

When a pull request is created:

Clone repository
Build Docker image
Run tests inside container
Fail if anything breaks
CD (Deploy)

When code is pushed to the main branch:

Build a new Docker image
Tag the image (e.g., latest or commit hash)
Push the image to Docker Hub
SSH into the server using stored secrets
Pull the latest image on the server
Stop old container and start new one

Example deployment logic:

docker pull username/app:latest        # fetch latest image
docker stop app_container             # stop old container
docker rm app_container               # remove old container
docker run -d -p 3000:3000 --name app_container username/app:latest  
# start updated container
End-to-End Flow

You write code and push it to GitHub. A CI/CD pipeline builds a Docker 
image and pushes it to Docker Hub. Your server then pulls that image and 
runs it as a container. This removes dependency issues and ensures the same 
environment runs everywhere.
